r job\nhas purpose and autonomy and affords them a good living. Jeff Bezos may not\nhave been passionate about APIs, but he was passionate about something (e.g.,\nearning money, putting his weewee in a girl with big boobs, etc) that drove\nhim to scholastic achievement and decades of working long hours well beyond\nwhat normal people would have tolerated, and for him selling stuff on the\ninternet was the mechanism for achieving the goals he was passionate about.\n\nMost people are like this\u2013we start out with goals like \u201cmaking a lot of money\u201d\nbut in the process we get caught up in details like caring about programming\nlanguages and the minutia of what language has what feature and we end up\narguing passionately about static typing as a surrogate for whatever we\nactually care about.\n\nReply\n\n  4. Derrick H Bonsell said, on April 16, 2024 at 1:49 pm\n\nI don\u2019t have anything profound to offer but this is a good post as usual.\n\nReply\n\n  5. Vadim Fedorovsky said, on April 16, 2024 at 4:07 pm\n\nThis is a really good post. I will show my children.\n\nRe: Aristotle Moralia\n\nDo you mean Nicomachean Ethics or what else?\n\nReply\n\n     * Scott Locklin said, on April 16, 2024 at 6:35 pm\n\nThey\u2019re all basically the same (I assume they\u2019re all somebody else\u2019s notes)\nbut Nicomachean is canon so just read that.\n\nReply\n\n  6. Frank said, on April 16, 2024 at 4:56 pm\n\nlol. People who are passionate about this or that on linkedin are usually\nwankers, we know this, but most of this article is a load of wank too. Thanks\nfor the tips anyway.\n\nReply\n\n  7. Altitude Zero said, on April 16, 2024 at 6:11 pm\n\nOf course, life is more pleasant when you like what you do for a living, are\ngood at it, and believe that it is important. But as usual, various nerds,\nstrives, and fanatics have to take this commonsensical commonplace\nobservation, and turn it up to eleven...\n\nReply\n\n  8. Chris O said, on April 16, 2024 at 6:50 pm\n\