 law act is done for now,\nbut perhaps I overestimate the VC. There are other types of course.\n\nReply\n\n             * Lev said, on April 18, 2024 at 2:00 pm\n\nDefinitely overestimate the VC.\n\nThe endless chase of the \u201cNext Bug Thing\u201d stops for no one.\n\nA few months back I was at a Google organized thing, where it seems like\ngoogle gives someone a bit of money, in exchange for the government giving\nthem a shitload of money to collect and process piles of useless data.\n\nReply\n\n             * chiral3 said, on April 18, 2024 at 2:52 pm\n\nRebekah Neumann (wife of WeWork Adam) has a ton of entertainment value. She\nstrikes me like a reincarnated version of Marshall Applewhite cum Sunny\nBalwani at a placenta party.\n\nReply\n\n  9. Rajan Meru said, on April 16, 2024 at 11:02 pm\n\n\u201cThey tell themselves nonsense like this to grub up the status pole with their\nwives boyfriends\u201d\n\nCasually invoking cuckoldry to shame bourgeois, UMC types will never not get a\nchuckle out of me.\n\nReply\n\n  10. Rickey said, on April 17, 2024 at 1:39 am\n\nMost of the successful persons I personally know are not passionate about\ntheir jobs or career. They are merely serious persons of average intelligence\nwho practice, prepare and are conscientious about the quality of their work.\nIt still surprises me how persons arrive for anything from a business meeting\nto choir practice completely unprepared and disorganized and just wing it and\nexpect good results. They are nothing but parasites to the successful.\n\nAs far as making the world a better place, subsidiarity is the best method for\nmost. Simply grabbing a shopping cart in the middle of the lot on your way\ninto a store, picking up a piece of trash instead of stepping over it, helping\nyour elderly neighbor with his hard work, etc. are just a few examples. Just\nbeing courteous to strangers would also help immensely.\n\nSending mad stacks of aid to the Haitians or \u201cPalestinians\u201d funded by\ntaxpayers may make some people feel better but that is like giving an IV to a\npatient that refuses to put pressure on his bleeding jugular vein. You can\u2019t\nhelp people that refuse to help themselves.\n\nReply\n\n  11. Alex Chandy said, on April 17, 2024 at 3:12 am\n\nRecently read how the hierarchy of workers can be simplified into 3 layers\n\n1\\. the builders/producers 2. the optimizers 3. the regulators\n\nGenerally, finance/consulting/banking industry can be defined as a Layer 2 of\na society , to make innovations made at Layer 1 by problem solvers more\nefficient.\n\nFinance and markets are great, to gain immediate efficiencies in innovations,\nbut that fades away quickly, then we hit the diminishing returns.\n\nAs being witnessed in companies like Boeing who has traded a lot of layer 1\nfor layer 2, it is a societal problem where 60% of workforce shifted from\n\u201cproblem solvers \u2013 Layer 1\u201d to \u201cefficiency creators \u2013 Layer 2\u201d essentially\nalso growing the Layer 3 (regulators, law) from a healthy 10% to 20%\n\nWe basically have upside down societies in West where, 20% solve problems in\nLayer 1, 60% create efficiencies in Layer 2, and 20% try to regulate the Layer\n2 since it is so unnecessarily huge and full of scams.\n\nImo, this upside down triangle evolved because of short termist incentives\ndesigns combined with follow your passion and exit at a large profit, in all\nlayers of the workforce (ie \u2013 Engineer wants to build a quick consumer app and\nexit quickly rather than work on a hard problem, Wall St. wants to take that\nconsumer app public and mainly dump unprofitable business model on public,\nregulator wants to be re-elected in the next 2 years)\n\nReply\n\n  12. redneckcryonicist said, on April 17, 2024 at 7:10 am\n\nFor some reason the pro-free market people don\u2019t want to talk about the\nproblems caused by successful capitalists who use their wealth, business\nskills and other assets to promote the socially damaging projects they are\n\u201cpassionate\u201d about. Friedrich Engels is the classic example of the capitalist\nwith a damaging passion: After Engels made bank from working for the\nManchester branch of his family\u2019s textile company, he spent his retirement\nyears applying his fortune and human capital towards marketing Marxism like it\nwas a company\u2019s product, with his friend Karl Marx as the company\u2019s brand.\nEngels even wrote and published the first \u201cDummies\u201d-style literature about\nMarxism to make it more accessible to less educated people.\n\nEngels was the organized and competent half of the Marx/Engels partnership;\nand without his efforts to get other socialists to accept Marxism as their\nideology (it had competitors in the late 19th Century), Marx\u2019s legacy wouldn\u2019t\nhave amounted to much.\n\nReply\n\n  13. Foo said, on April 18, 2024 at 12:54 pm\n\nThis is absolutely right. I have been quite discriminating against people who\nclaim they\u2019re passionate about what I\u2019m hiring them for, and doubly so when\nthey appear to be genuine in saying that.\n\nThere\u2019s a major issue, which is that people who are passionate about work are\noften given to other delusions, like that their work matters to the world in a\ndeep way. Or that they, personally, are very important in some way, and have a\nmission. I already dodged a very bad bullet recently with this approach.\n\nNarcissists make for unreliable, difficult employees, and are the source of\nsome of the negative nerd stereotypes. The \u201csuperstar diva\u201d nerd, the \u201ccan\u2019t\ntake criticism nerd\u201d, the \u201cprofit is irrelevant\u201d nerd. All very passionate\nabout nerdery, all very passionate about themselves and/or their place in the\nworld. Screw that. Just do a good job, because it\u2019s a fair thing to do (since\nwe have a contract to that effect and I am paying you perfectly genuine\nbucks), and put your passion into birding, gym or something else.\n\nReply\n\n     * chiral3 said, on April 18, 2024 at 1:54 pm\n\nI get a kick out of the nerd cross-over types. In general, three types of\ncorporate nerds: the spergos that need extra management / guide rails and\nconstant sperg-centric therapy sessions when they freak out over someone using\na design pattern or estimation method that renders them apoplectic. These\nnerds have real skills, limited upward mobility, and hash out a normal career\nthat is marked by constant stress and difficult bonus-time conversations\n(\u201cyes, your code did speed things up 10x... we didn\u2019t ask for that, but I love\nthe initiative and creativity... even if you spent three months\nrefactoring.... I am sorry, you got a 4, which is great, you should be proud,\nand you\u2019re getting 148% of target, plus I popped your total comp by 25%, but I\ncan\u2019t pay you X million dollars exrtra because you think the speed up was\nworth that...\u201d) Second type are the kids that are essentially buffs and they\nhit a wall with their abilities. These types hop jobs in the ecosystem till\nthey are outed, then they move to adjacent industry and wring that chamois\nusing basically the same skills (eg hedge funds to trad fi to fintec to ed\ntech, typically a trend towards saving the world with code... oddly first gen\nfintech types tend to stay and not xover). Third type is the chameleon-nerd:\nthe person that cosplayed a nerd and they are dark-triad enough that they\nmorph into whatever the hypegeist is at that zeit. These creatures have no\ndiscernible skills and can climb a ladder because they don\u2019t make management\nfeel like idiots when they speak. They are probably talking to boards about AI\nbecoming sentient and burning their companies to the ground as I write this. A\nfew years ago they were yammering about big data; before that robotics and\nnano-automation. They typically have (only) an undergrad degree from a decent\nschool (MIT comes to mind as a factory of these people). They like to give\ntalks about nothing concrete and really hit the Theranos-esque passion of the\ntech pablum. Lotsa \u201cthere\u2019s known knowns, known unknowns, and unknown\nunknowns\u201d coupled with endless and nebulous talk about leadership (quoting\nNavy SEAL influencers, Colin Powell, and Sun Szu). If they are sixty years old\nthey are still hawking their undergrad alma mater as a credential to boards\nsince every board needs one spergo to check the box on having someone ask\nquestions like \u201cis there a p-value for that?\u201d.\n\nReply\n\n       * Foo said, on April 18, 2024 at 2:38 pm\n\nWell, you can add \u201cactivist nerd\u201d to this list now. They pop up every now and\nthen, but have been getting really insufferable. They have real skills, but\ninstead of trying to convert them to cash like your spergo-nerd (sperd?),\nbeing able to write half-decent Rust ought to give them dictatorial powers\nover broad company policy. Some might even stage a sit-in.\n\nAs to the rest of your list \u2013 pretty spot on. I deliberately stayed within my\narea of competence, but outside my area of interest, with my professional\nlife. I think that\u2019s how you can avoid falling into both traps (that of\nbecoming an incompetent x-over grifter, and that of becoming a superstar diva\n/ activist / etc).\n\nReply\n\n         * chiral3 said, on April 18, 2024 at 2:59 pm\n\nI have literally been in this meeting. It is uncanny.\n\nReply\n\n       * Scott Locklin said, on April 18, 2024 at 3:24 pm\n\nVery accurate taxonomy.\n\nReply\n\n### Leave a comment Cancel reply\n\n### About me:\n\n  * Consulting services\n  * Stuff I like\n  * The Futurist Manifesto\n  * About Scott Locklin\n\n### Past blogs\n\nJoin 2,325 other subscribers\n\n### RSS link thingee\n\n  * RSS - Posts\n  * RSS - Comments\n\nBlog at WordPress.com.\n\n  * Comment\n  * Reblog\n  * Subscribe Subscribed\n\n    * Locklin on science\n    * Already have a WordPress.com account? Log in now.\n\n  *  